  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "DeDCmYi8BUfB5tiU1drotiNHaZ0=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:47.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "# truthy checks are safer than undefined checks for optional state assignment\n\nWhen conditionally assigning optional input values to state:\n\n```typescript\n// \u274c Type error \u2014 'string | null' is not assignable to 'string'\nif (action.input.field !== undefined) entry.field = action.input.field;\n\n// \u2705 Truthy check handles both null and undefined\nif (action.input.field) state.field = action.input.field;\n\n// \u2705 For booleans, use explicit null/undefined checks\nif (action.input.field !== undefined && action.input.field !== null)\n  state.field = action.input.field;\n```\n\nThe truthy check works because both `null` and `undefined` are falsy. For boolean fields, you cannot use truthy checks since `false` is also falsy \u2014 use explicit null/undefined guards instead.\n\nSince [[nullable input types require explicit coalescing to match state types]], this pattern complements the `|| null` coalescing approach for different assignment scenarios.\n\n---\n\nTopics:\n- [[reducer patterns]]",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:47.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:47.000Z"
    }
  },
